segments.text: This is great.
So, okay, okay.
Now, targets in Laos.

Now, generally speaking, the Ho Chi Minh Trail, we got to the point where we operated so much, we didn't know just about where it was, but you know, the Ho Chi Minh Trail was like ants passing through your lawn.
You stop them up one direction, they move over a hundred feet and go through the jungle and establish another one.
Nobody can really understand this capability of the Viet Cong in getting supplies down that Ho Chi Minh Trail from North Vietnam to South Vietnam until they've actually seen it.
Then you can understand it.
It's almost unbelievable for me to describe it and for you to believe that there's no reason why we couldn't stop these supplies.
But when men have an A-frame on their back and will carry
hundred-pound loads on their back and walk through the jungle under complete canopy, which you can't even penetrate with film, then maybe you understand.
And they walked all the way.
Bicycles, they'd ride bicycles there.
If I'm getting off the subject.
We knew generally where these routes were, and at night they felt they were free to
down the usual trail, because nobody could see them.
Well, of course, this stopped when we got the gunship capability over there that had the night vision for the infrared flare, which would go by Texas Institute.
And again, I was very proud of getting this introduced into the combat forces over there.
But there were at times where we knew there were concentrations of supplies, you know, and relays to go from one day and one night, then stop, then the next

night they'd go another maybe 10 or 12 miles and they'd stop and always move at night we you know eventually find these concentrations and it always turned out that wherever these concentrations were sure enough there'd be some AA defense from them operated by Pathet Laos now this up down Laos because they knew if we found them we're going to hit them well they're going to start trying to protect them with AA and eventually got to be very capable so it built radar directed AA in Laos
This is not very well known.
But these targets had to be hit, and this was General Mulmire's responsibility.
He had to- one of the basic doctors of air force, of course, air tactics, you've got to hit them in the supply area where it hurts the top supply.
Interdiction, if you will.
Tactical air warfare.
Now, did he have authority to hit these targets?
Well, he had to properly identify them and get permission from Ambassador Sullivan's
to hit these targets.
It required communications that had made things more complex and halted.
It hindered operations, but it worked.
But when these particular targets might, let's say, be near a, let's say, a habitated center, I call it an inhabited center, a town, if you will, in Laos,
which, if you bomb there, it maybe hits civilians.
And this is where the problems came up.
This was forbidden, absolutely forbidden.
You cannot hit certain targets in Laos.
Well, in warfare, sometimes, you know, it's difficult.
Particularly in the jungle of the southeast states, it's hard to identify targets at best.
But sometimes mistakes were made.
And we'd hit targets, and we'd kill civilians.
And this was when the fire would fly between Ambrose Sullivan and
Seventh Air Force.
And again, this was a matter of refereeing and arbitration, where I came into picture.
A lot of cases where nothing were but saving people's feelings, and Ambassador Sullivan was well aware of the difficulties we had in those places.
What were some of these places that you were hitting, and do you remember any of the major accidents, so to speak?
No, just a matter of fact, at night, a bomber, a fighter bomber, misidentifying the target, or maybe even missing the target, and screwing his bomb across the city.
Understandable era, definitely not intentional, but generally that's what it was.
I don't remember any gross eras like hitting a dam.
That never did come.
What were some of the, what about the targets?
Did you ever get any of these Russian installations?
Russian?
No, did you ever get any of these installations?
I thought you said they had some AA.
Oh, yes, as a matter of fact.
You said in Laos.
Oh, yeah, we lost airplanes in Laos.
Okay, did you ever, those were targeted, weren't they?
Yeah.
Were they knocked down?
We had airplanes knocked down by AA fire in Laos.
As a matter of fact, one of the
One of the most dangerous and difficult targets for pilots, and boy, they thought twice when they were trying to hit that target, was a pass.

I forget the name of it, but it was just in the southeast, southwestern corner of North Vietnam across the mountains into Laos, just at, you might say, the point where North Vietnam and South Vietnam came together at the demilitarized zone.
Yeah.
where Laos was on the western border of both of them.
There was a pass through there, a mountain pass.
And this was, you know, the pass normally is where most of the roads are in transportation nationally.
So that's where the Ho Chi Minh Trail went through there.
And we knew there were foreign supplies through there.
And it got where we started hitting them.
Well, the more we struck it, the more they put AA defenses there.
The more we drank it, the more they put better AA defenses in there.
Finally, they got these radar-controlled defenses.
Boy, it was a tough target.
It was almost like going against a barrel of a cannon.
To my knowledge, I don't ever remember a missile as such, a SAM, ever being deployed in Laos.
I don't think the Russians would permit the North Vietnamese to do it.
But they got radar-controlled AA weapons.
and we lost airplanes.
And I don't ever remember us losing an airplane over Laos to a MiG.
The MiGs in North Vietnam, they very, very seldom would ever fly over into Thailand, or Laos.
And I don't ever remember a MiG coming into South Vietnam.
And maybe their rules were different.
I don't know.
Now I do remember we lost a C-47 in northern stretches of Laos.
We had strayed and got off course and got too close to the North Vietnam border.
It may have actually been within North Vietnam and it was intercepted by a MiG and shot down.
We know this by the pilot
calling in and saying, I'm being attacked.
We lost the airplane with all the people on it.
Was he killed, or did he ever come back?
Was he killed?
The whole crew was killed.
Everybody aboard.
No one bailed out?
They were shot down.
That was one of the roads through the air.
Yeah.
Okay.
Now, how
Tell me about, you said you had a few Air American people on your base.
On the Thai Air Base.
Yeah.
In fact, I was there too, but this was on the Thai Air Base.
Exactly, but I know at Udorn.
What about, did you meet any of these people?
Oh, yeah.
I ate dinner with them many, matter of fact, they had such a terrific mess on Sunday, I always went over and had dinner at their mess hall on Sunday.
No kidding.
Fantastic.
You had good relations with them.
As a matter of fact, you see this carried me back to my earlier days as a member of the Flying Tigers.
Sure, because they were in a sense a similar outfit, weren't they?
Exactly.
They had what was called, incidentally, they did better than we did though, financial wise, they had
what they called a $100,000 club.
See, this outfit had been over a long, long time before we got in the war.
And they were paid terrific salaries.
Do you remember what it was, how much you were paid?
No, I don't, but $100,000 club was a man who became a member of it when he had earned $100,000.
And I know some of them have been over a few years.
In one year?
Oh, no, no, no.
Two or three years.
Two or three years they could make $100,000?
By various means.
This wasn't all paid.
Were they former Air Force pilots, most of them?
Yeah, some of them were.
Half of them, would you say?
I don't know.
I don't know that much about the exact organization.
I'd say they had about, they must have had about always a total of at least six or eight helicopters.
Sometimes, see, they had them across the river at the airport at Ben 10.
But their main maintenance base and major supply and maintenance, if you will, depot level was right there on the base of Udorn.
They had two or three C-123s, and they must have had, or they had to have at least 150 people.
A hundred and fifty at Udorn?
It's a big operation.
Between Udorn and Vientiane.
It's a big operation.
Oh, are you kidding?
Of course.

Well, now that doesn't include the big supply base they had down at Tocqueville where they actually stored and eventually had a supply operation, I mean a supply storage space right there at my base at Udorn.
I had to provide an extra ramp.
We actually built it for them.
An extra ramp and hangar, well if you will, a supply warehouse where they stored their
their bombs and their what they called A packages of rice and clothing, medicine.
Were they all American citizens or were there some foreigners?
No, no, all Americans.
Some Laotian and some Thais.
I might even enlighten you on even another type of operation that's probably very, very little known.
I actually got involved in coordination, and you can imagine the people involved, between the Thais, the Laotians, the two ambassadors, and Air America, and and me, of moving some Thai army
artillery over into Laos to actually help them in their fighting.
Man by ties.
Really?
And you transported them up there?
Or did Air American transport them?
Air American transported them.
How many went up there?
Oh, it was a very small operation.
Just so you might know, they had detachment with maybe two or three pieces of artillery.
How effective it was, I don't know.
I didn't.
Did they go up there to train LAO's?
Oh no, they fight well.
Fight for them.
Probably went up to train them, but that meant fighting too.
This was when the General Mao, M-E-O, and his, see there were good Pathet Maos and bad Pathet Laos.
He was the good Pathet Lao.
When he was being hard pressed and pushed back south,
towards Vientiane by the North Vietnamese and Northeastern Laos in a determined effort to wipe him out.
The North Vietnamese decided to eliminate him.
He was a very effective little ragtag force, if you will, and completely supported by the CIA.
And when he was being pushed and needed some support, well, the Thais tried to help.
Well, that's the type of thing, one of the types of things I got involved in.
The Thais were, they were afraid of the North Vietnamese.
Oh, yeah.
In fact, this, when I mentioned insurrectionists in northern Thailand, it was obvious a lot of them were North Vietnamese.
Or, if you will, Thailand

What, North Vietnamese refugees had come down into northern Thailand and then were subverted and trained and then sent back, you know, got back to North Vietnam, then were trained and paid accordingly, and then stepped back into North Thailand as a, really as a North Vietnamese agent.
It got awful sticky and complicated.
But as I say, it was extremely interesting.
No kidding.
Now, when Thailand sent these artillery men over, and the two or three pieces of artillery, did they dress them in Laotian uniforms?
I don't remember, but I do know this, that I doubt it.
I got an idea that they had just, if you will, the black uniform on.
Maybe it wasn't.
It may have been just black pajamas.
The term black I use, as a matter of fact, that defines this type of an operation.
It's a black operation.
This is the CIA term.
In other words, unknown, you can't see it, or words of that effect.
But I remember it, and we often laugh about it on my staff, C-123 would come in some night at Udorn.
No markings on it whatsoever, not even any numbers.
No markings on it whatsoever.
Painted black.
The plane was painted black?
Painted black.
And land.

And we always grabbed a lot of little bitty men that all of a sudden flow out of this thing, an Air America vehicle, pick them all up, put them in this truck, close the end of the truck with the curtain, and take them off to a special barracks.
It was not part of my responsibility
on the Udorn Air Base, and close the doors.
And you go by there in daytime, you'd never see anybody, and you wouldn't even know what's going on.

But the following night, about midnight, a truck come up, all these little piece of men would get out and get in this truck, and the truck would run up to this airplane, this black airplane for it, and it would open up, and they'd get in the back of this and see it's an airlift like the airplane.
Sure.
And I'm talking about thirty or forty people.
All these little bitty men would get in there and they, you know at night they looked black.
How they were dressed we don't know.
God knows they were probably dressed in typical civilian garb of the Laotian countrymen or peasants living in the jungle.
That's probably the way they were dressed.
And then this airplane had planned upon running me to take off and head over into the lounge.
You didn't know who they were?
Did you ever find out anything?
Did you ever ask?
Oh, yeah.
We, at times, various times, get sufficient answers to know that these were special paid and special trained jungle warfare people by the CIA.
And some of them were actually laid on by General Westmoreland's command down in Saigon.
to be carried over into the Laotian area and some landing zone, as we called it, a big enough area where the airplane could land and let them get out.
And then by their training and all, they, coming from that area, they knew exactly the countryside.
And then they would station themselves along the Ho Chi Minh Trail and actually report back
in some cases by radio, and in some cases by just recording information and maintaining data, and then being picked up, let's say, three nights later on the flow of supplies down.
And sometimes, actually, the instructions to lay on ambushes and kill North Vietnamese coming down North Vietnam, this type of operation.
A lot of this went on.
A lot of it.
How free were the Air America people in discussing these actions with you when you went over there on Sunday and had a brunch with them?
They were very well-trained in this area.
They didn't talk about it.
They were unusually well-trained.
And I knew better than to ask the question, quite frankly.
They'd talk about some of the resupply missions in the area.
I'd go up to LZ-2, Leningrad 2, and
stuff off some rice.
They'd talk about things like that.
That was why they'd be shot at.
Boy, I got a bullet hole today.
They lost a few pilots and helicopters.
Again, it carried me back to my experience.
And if they were supplying someplace and they were shot down, and they were captured,
What would they do?
Would they say they were American citizens?
What kind of papers would they have on them?
Did you ever find out?
No, I don't think they were carrying papers on them.
I'm sure a lot of the...
I'll tell you what, I'll bet you some would think about it.
I imagine a lot of the experience in their operations probably was copied from some of our experience in Flying Tigers.
I don't remember them carrying any identification on their back like we did.
as part of the, in other words, as part of the Laotian Air Force.
I don't know of any occasions where one of them was captured.
I don't ever remember this being brought up.
I know some were killed.
Yeah, they were shot down there.
I got an idea that one of them was captured.
He was probably shot.
I don't know.
And that's the reason they were high paid.
They knew that.
They definitely were flying at me.

As a matter of fact, I had to coordinate a mission one time where actually we flew aircraft over and provided air cover for one of their operations that was so close to the front of the North Vietnam in Laos.
You know, sometimes we did get in air support with them.
But that was unusual.
What kind of mission was that?

It was a resupply, but they had to drop supplies to General Miles' forces so close to where the fighting front, if you will, between the North Vietnamese that they were apt to be fired at by the North Vietnamese and shot down.
So you sent a couple of jets over there.
Yeah, to suppress.
And just the appearance of the jets alone would keep the North Vietnamese from firing.
This happened two or three times.

And actually, we, in coordination through my control center between Ambassador Sullivan's control center in Laos and General Mulminer's headquarters, we actually laid on some strike missions with my F-4s and F-105s and Thailand bases against the North Vietnamese when they were really swarming down against the Laotians when they were approaching the capital of Vientiane.
at Ambassador Sullivan's request.
That's one time Ambassador Sullivan got in bed with General Martin.
He needed his support.
And the provided one.
This was a war that was very little publicized.
Oh, absolutely.
Very little publicized.
Not until the Pentagon gave us, did you?
Okay, well, we're doing a great job here.
So the Air America people, you had a
have a good sized contingency of them.
I'm surprised at the numbers.
Well, I may be overestimated, but it's bound to be that many total.
OK. Now let's turn to the Special Forces Air Force group.
Tell me about their capabilities.
You mentioned before that you thought they were outstanding.
This was the OB-26 twin engine, basically a light bomber, attack type aircraft, and little AT-6, I believe that's what they were called, T-26, T-26, T-26, trainer 26 aircraft, little single engine
It's really a trainer airplane.
It could carry two 250-pound bombs, something like that.
It had guns in it, but when we give these type of aircraft to Thailand or to Laos or to South Vietnamese, they'd put guns on it, use it as an attack airplane, a fighter.
But, you know, definitely was not comparable to modern fighter.
But they were slow, relatively slow compared to jet aircraft.
They could fly at night, just like an airplane.
But being slower, you had greater time to identify a target and greater maneuverability to attack it and say, less room for error.
I mean, much more room and latitude for making an error and being able to correct your position in order to actually put a bomb on a target.
This is a controversial thing and was, and to a certain extent still is, in the Air Force.
Do you want a slow aircraft to provide ground air support, or do you want and need a modern jet, a high-speed jet, to provide close air support and ground attack?

it uh some people say it's controversial in uh in real high threat warfare you definitely have to have the high-speed jet otherwise you wouldn't live you'd be shut down now in a jungle warfare and particularly over there where you don't have a high defense to go against then this light airplane is much better and that's the reason we had some special forces in thailand in a certain area and that's the reason they were
employed in that particular area.
We didn't expect the North Vietnamese ever to get any sophisticated anti-aircraft down the Ho Chi Minh Trail.
That's where these special forces drove them.
That's right.
See, that's the reason they were assigned there.
So this doesn't, you have to understand all this.
Some decisions you think might be idiotic and you don't understand them, but really this was a sound decision.
The only thing that Momar got teed off about, TWD, was that
He wanted modern forces.
He didn't want any kind of an airplane over there except a jet aircraft.
And he wanted, of course, he wanted primarily to knock out the supply sewers.
In other words, hit North Vietnam.
The way we should have done it, anyhow.
But here, part of his forces using up one of his base was these little top-driven aircraft.
Bomar strenuously objected to it.
But Ambassador Sullivan, having, you know, a certain authority and responsibility in Laos, obviously overruled, so we got the Air Force forces there.
Well, now what's the capability?
At night, and particularly on moonlight night, in this little slow T-26 with a cup of 250 pound bomb, and with guns on it, 30 caliber guns,
against open targets, let's say a truck that you could see on a moonlight night and didn't have any tree cover.
Gee, this was our plan perfect to knock it out, and they got trucks.
The B-26, which had a much greater bomb capability and many more guns on it, it had a much greater capability than the T-26, and it did a good job.
And our daily truck count, which we had every morning, debriefings, you know, stand-up briefings, what we do last night,
These little forces always had some truck kills, or maybe an anti-aircraft site suppression.
They actually attacked and destroyed the state government.
Whereas the F-4s based at Ubon that were special trained for night bombing missions along the
I remember talking to some pilots that flew that aircraft on that type of mission, and boy, it was a hairy operation at night.
Also- They could hear you coming to them.
Well, no more than you could hear the T-26 coming.
But so, I mean, they get from the ground, the North Vietnamese could hear this airplane flying so slowly that they could probably have, what, a few seconds warning that this bomber's coming?
Well, or is that-
Now, more sight, seeing one, than hearing.
The hearing was not that much different, but the sight of seeing it, you know.
But at night they wouldn't see it.
No, at night.
But then, of course, you blew your lights, running lights off.
Sure.

But operating an F-4 and trying to find your target at a high speed and then at a higher altitude and making the diving pass and then recovering at night and, you know, whether it's moonlight night or not, you had to go.
Boy, this was like flying in a, well, it was difficult.
Difficult task, and kind of hairy, and it took special training.

But they killed trucks, but none of them were as effective as what we called a gunship, a C-130, specially equipped, that we eventually got into the base at Ubon, and they were given a primary mission.
of operations against the Ho Chi Minh Trail.
Now this was a very effective Tell me about this one.
This is a normal C-130 four-engine turboprop transport that you've seen with Transport Truth.
It was manned with side firing out the side of the fuselage.
Automatic turret-type
machine gun operations with 20 millimeter, and we eventually even experimented with putting as high as a cannon, what we called a cannon, 75 millimeter.
Wow.
How did that work?
We experimented with it at Eglin, but it didn't get an operation for a while.
I wasn't over there whether it ever got an operation.
Didn't that stress on the client?
recall was automatically taken care of by suppression of recall.

But this was a very effective 50 caliber, 20 millimeter gun firing, you know, and special maneuver that the airplane would go into and actually trace the fire, you know, the pilot would fly the airplane when he'd locate the truck.
It was clear before looking in for red.
And coordination, you'd be really

on your toes and just absolutely enthralled to hear a tape recording of the coordination by radio teletype, I mean radio telegraphy, you know, earphones, and transmitting the aircraft between the pilot flying the airplane and the gunner back there, and a coordination between all of them.
And let's say the scanner's looking out, you know, by just looking out the side of the airplane.

and protected the guy, let's say watching the FLIR, before looking at the red display where the truck was, in this turning maneuver, and then firing on these trucks at night, and also taking pictures of them, of the FLIR presentation, you know, on another scope, and seeing the truck explode.
It was absolutely
It's amazing to watch this operation.
Extremely effective.
And boy, I tell you, those were effective operations.
But a gunship put out just thousands of rounds per second.
Now, I'm telling you so many things that I may be getting my nomenclature mixed up.
But I'll try to get all this straightened out about the caliber, the size, and the types, the name, and all, when I go through these.
Well, you used the gunships then.
Yes, and they were fragged by John Wilmer, 7th Air Force.
All of them were based as a unit.
We had about, I think we had a unit of about six of them at Ubon, Thailand, right near Littleson border.
Gunships.
Okay.
Now, let me add this.
As a result of this type of operation, particularly the Special Forces people, you know, who dedicated their mission They didn't fly gunships, did they?
No, no, no, no.
But Special Forces people wanted it because, boy, that was an advanced weapon, and that's right down their alley, see.
But this was sort of a new innovation in tactical warfare.
As a matter of fact, General Lohmeyer monitored this very carefully personally, and it turned out to be very effective.
And even some of the people, you know, said, gee, we ought to have this thing in Europe, you know, with such effective operations against ground forces.
That thing would not live in a classical air battle area.
It'd be shot down and nothing left.
Oh, yeah, it had no defense.
But at nighttime, now, it'd be a little bit different operation.
But in my opinion, that thing would have no place in the classical war in Europe.
But in your opinion, the job that it did in jungle warfare?
Terrific.
Terrific.
It's still a part of the Special Weapons Forces.
It's still a part of Tactical Air Warfare Special Forces and TAC at Hurlburt Air Force in Florida.
As a matter of fact, they're still improving it technologically.
And I'm sure, I don't know this, but I'm sure they're still experimenting with higher caliber weapons than they should be.
Okay.

incidentally that airplane also can carry a laser marker and mark mark at night mark a target with the laser uh laser designator and the fighter flying with it can drop a bomb at night not ever even see the target but drop the bombs that work uh disclose coordination no but i mean how do they

don't understand the technology behind this well the laser guide bomb on the fighter detects when it dropped if it's dropped in the envelope of the flying pattern between the in the area of the target on the ground where the laser designator it's a laser itself in the airplane marks a spot it puts a laser on this target let's say it's a let's say it's a truck he just shines his laser on the truck now the
The laser emitter, the laser energy hitting a truck emits energy.
The laser detector on the nose of the bomb, once it's dropped from the airplane, picks that up and hones on it.
General S. Merlin said that this is the most technological war in American history.
He would, right, matter of fact.
Well, in history.
Oh, yeah.
He's absolutely right.
I agree with him.
OK. Now that we're on technology in Vietnam, are there other examples of new Air Force technology that's used besides a gunship and these small airplanes?
And we talked about the laser bomb.
Anything else?
Oh, yeah, in the field of reconnaissance.
Protectable electronics.
Well, in electronic warfare, there were many new advancements in the technology of ECM, both detection, jamming, and jam-free type of equipment, guidance equipment.
It was really a proving ground for the field of electronic, electromagnetic warfare.
It was really a proving ground.
Matter of fact, a lot of the things we learned over there are currently oriented to, you know, the universal warfare.
We talked about the laser-guided bomb.
Phenomenal, the rope.
had its disadvantages compared to the new HARM, H-A-R-M weapon, in range, in particular speed.
What is the HARM missile?
The HARM is the same thing.
It's an advanced strike.
Both of them made it.
Air-to-air?
No, air-to-surface.
For the same purpose.
SAM suppression, if you will.
Surface-to-air missile.
And how does the HARM work?
The same way the strike does.

except it has a much greater capability has a longer range it's supersonic very fast and therefore more effective it has a greater capability to pick up electronic emissions in other words the sound sight it has well i'm talking about a modern weapon now i better keep my mouth shut
We still have the harms in our arsenal, then.
Okay, I wanted to ask if we had nuclear capabilities in Thailand.
Actually employed and deployed horses, no.
But you remember I mentioned B-52s?
Sure.
They were operating with, incidentally, carrying 50, 60 bombs.
Sure.
You know, B-52 was readily convertible to nuclear weapons.
Oh, absolutely.

There's no doubt that we could have, well, you know, we could introduce, we could have taken a B-52 off of the United States and dropped a nuclear weapon from the United States if we wanted to, if it was ever necessary.
I don't know if we could operate them out with nuclear weapons or Mokinawa, couldn't we?
Sure.
So we didn't have them in Thailand.
Or Navy carriers, I'm sure, had the Navy.
Now you said that, I wanted to ask a question about insignias.
When you were in the area, at Udorn, all your airplanes had American insignias on them.
because the ranch hands who did the spraying and the defoliant, and I told you I knew a colonel, a lieutenant colonel who was one of the pilots of the ranch hands, they changed the insignias at will.
I mean when they were
They'd put Thai insignias on their airplanes, they'd put Laotian insignias, they'd put South Vietnamese insignias, and they'd always change depending on where they were going to spray.
But you didn't ever change yours?
Well, I never had defoliant portions in Thailand.
They always operate out of South Vietnam.
So you never had any dealings with the defoliant?
No.
Okay, you also said that
naval air bomber strikes were a tough task, and I said we'd get back to that.
Now tell me about that, naval air bomber strikes.
Well, here again, you know, it's goals and missions, and basic rules of warfare, if you will, that are well known by experienced air warfare people.
I mean, Navy and Air Force, and now, you know, some of the Army boys are operating aircraft of various types.
But basic principle, and I think it's well accepted by everybody.
I won't say that.
It is not well accepted by everybody.
That's the reason of the problem.
But definitely the Air Force.
Not accepted by the Navy now?
Apparently not.
Okay.
What is it now?
In any...

war in particular a theater of operations a particular area where there's got to be joint operations of either two or more forces army air force army navy army navy and air force and let's say throw in a marine and let's say throw in the cia as i've been telling you about let's throw throw in a special weapon special forces which are part of the airport there's got to be one air commander
Now, this is basic Air Force doctrine, and I agree with it 100%.
If there was an advocate of this, it was little Spike Momar.
He agreed with it, of course.
Well, General Momar, being a very dedicated man to his job, and particularly Air Force, and probably, in my opinion, not probably, but it was, in my opinion, definitely,
the best and most capable tactical Air Force general we had in the entire Air Force at the time he was assigned Seventh Air Force.
As a matter of fact, that's the reason he was assigned Seventh Air Force.
And I say this out of pure respect, not just because he's classmate of mine, and I like him, but he made an issue of this when he was given Seventh Air Force, that he wanted control of
No, no.
Texas moment with any air cadets, flying cadets.
